t, Hastière, Flemish Brabant, Holy Roman Empire":"Agimont, Namur, Belgium","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"NESLE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Horst.","German: from a pet form of the female medieval personal name <i>Nes</i>, a short form of   Agnes  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Agnes","meanings":["English; French (<b>Agnès</b>); Hungarian (<b>Ágnes</b>): from a female personal name, which is from Late Latin <i>Agnes</i> and this one from Greek <i>Hagnē</i>, from <i>hagnē</i> ‘pure, chaste’. Saint Agnes was a Christian virgin martyr, one of those who suffered under the persecutions of Diocletian in 303  AD . Her name was associated by folk etymology with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, and in medieval art she is often depicted with a lamb (the lamb of God). See also English   Annis  .","American shortened (and altered) form of rare Greek metronymics <b>Agnidis</b> or <b>Agniadis</b>, both derived from the female personal name <i>Hagnē</i> (see 1 above), or of patronymics like   Anagnostopoulos   (compare   Agnew   4)."]}]},{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Marie DE NESLE DE FALVY-D'AUDENARDE was born in 1270, in France, her father, Jean IV de Nesle Comte de Soissons et Chimay, was 13 and her mother, Marie d'Audenarde, was 24. She had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Comte Jean II de Looz. She died in 1328, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1270–1328":"1270–1328","1272–1310":"1272–1310","1268–1310":"1268–1310","1321–1350":"1321–1350","–Male":"Surnud","1288–1323":"1288–1323","1297–1391":"1297–1391","–1345":"–1345","–1370":"–1370","1302–1358":"1302–1358","1258–1289":"1258–1289","1246–1290":"1246–1290","1297":"1297","1350":"1350","1272":"1272","19 JAN 1310":"19. jaanuar 1310","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1391":"1391","1290":"1290","circa 1297":"umbes 1297","1358":"1358","1258":"1258","1302":"1302","1246":"1246","1345":"1345","1323":"1323","1268":"1268","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1321":